,Recommended,258010,24681757,"Posted: 2 August, 2016",all,Admiral Squirg,"Very engaging singleplayer campaign, well written characters, concepts, and dialogue. Good variety of missions that can be tackled in numerous ways and won't bore you. Estimated length is 30~ hours. If the game was singleplayer only it would still be worth at least 20$ imho.Ship classes translate very well, casters, rogues, grapplers, etc all perform intuitively and if you like a certain playstyle in normal RPGs chances are you'll like them here as well. Furthermore, the ability to customize weapons, abilities, and ship handling is very in-depth without being overly complicated. All systems are rather basic but work together for a very deep experience. If you want to make a ship loadout that perfectly suits your combat style, you can. The developers certainly knew what they were doing here.Haven't really touched multiplayer, but you can do CO-OP missions or PvP using the ships you built in singleplayer. Lots of fun. Get this game for everyone you know that like games like FTL, Sunrider, or Infinite Space."
76561198001101593,Recommended,258010,26508220,"Posted: 9 November, 2016",all,Valinde,"Just found out I never gave this game a positive review despite playing the hell out of it, way back.The thing that got me interested in FOTS was the soundtrack, which I heard before playing the game itself, and it was dope AF. It's mostly upbeat, energetic and all awesome. It sticks with you for a while, since the graphics and art style, otherwise,  are average at best. It doesn't just kick♥♥♥♥♥ it leaves it marked for life.Next up, the gameplay. It's all top-down, very fast-paced, played with either mouse + keyboard or just keyboard. Interestingly, it borrows a bit from RPGs in that you can pick a ""ship class"", that mostly defines your playstyle and gear, from a dog-fighting, acrobatic fighter that shoots many lasers (personal favorite, maybe) to a big hulkin' missile boat THAT REQUIRES TWO PEOPLE TO FLY. WHAT ?You get to fly around the galaxy and meet people, it's pretty swell, yo. There's even a story thrown in that has you and various people, one inside your head, snarking away at the slightest nudge. Some moments are downright hilarious, which was very pleasantly surprising.It ain't all perfect though ! Most of the missions are very repetitive, either in the way of reused assets or objectives, or arena-like combat (though this particular trope/cliché/whatever is played on with a few twists) , and sometimes the game feels very rough around the edges. You don't navigate menus, you trudge through them. Outfitting ships is anything but intuitive. Escort missions are used too fookin' often, and the backstory is more plentiful on the fookin' trading cards than in-game ! What ?Other than that ? The music, man. I still listen to it, probably will for a while. It's that good. It makes the whole experience very, very much worth your while. After all, it'll stay with yo♥♥♥♥♥forever."
